summary.text: The sky appears blue due to Rayleigh scattering, where shorter wavelengths of light (blue) scatter more than longer wavelengths (red) in the atmosphere.

content.text: The sky is blue because of a phenomenon called Rayleigh scattering. When sunlight enters Earth's atmosphere, it collides with gas molecules. Blue light has a shorter wavelength and gets scattered more than other colors, making the sky appear blue to our eyes.
